rs do that? That=E2=80=99s what reporters do!=C2=A0

=C2=A0

For a lot of people I talk to, there was a kind of whiplash=E2=80=94like, o=
ne minute they=E2=80=99re calling Trump a fascist, the next minute they=E2=
=80=99re going down there and kissing his ring.

=C2=A0

First of all, John, you know me. Have you ever seen me kiss someone=E2=80=
=99s ring? You can tell anybody that if they can find one person=E2=80=99s
ring that I=E2=80=99ve ever kissed in my entire fucking life, you would giv=
e them however much money you want=E2=80=94because I don=E2=80=99t do that.=
 I didn=E2=80=99t do it in Congress. I haven=E2=80=99t done it in the TV bu=
siness. And I=E2=80=99m not doing it now.

My point to people has been: They do four hours a day of live TV=E2=80=94yo=
u can judge for yourself how they cover Trump and the administration going =
forward. If they start giving him tongue baths, then they=E2=80=99re guilty=
 as charged.
But if they continue to do tough coverage, who cares about a trip to Mar-a-=
Lago? The proof will be in the pudding.

=C2=A0

And what have we done since then? Whether it was Matt Gaetz or Pete Hegseth=
 or Kash Patel or Bobby Kennedy Jr., we=E2=80=99ve been hammering away nons=
top=E2=80=94just nonstop. The whole thing is fascinating because, as you sa=
id, we
do all this stuff in public. Four hours a day, 20 hours a week. And we=E2=
=80=99ve continued to do what we=E2=80=99ve always done.

=C2=A0

I will say, though, going back to your comment about never kissing rings: Y=
ou=E2=80=99d kiss Paul McCartney=E2=80=99s ring in a hot second. Let=E2=80=
=99s be honest.

=C2=A0

I would. He=E2=80=99s the one exception to the rule.

